output.crosstab_text:
Among those who graduated five years previously from level 7 (taught) courses in all subjects and who were working during the 2021-22 tax year, the industry with the highest proportion of graduates was the same for both female and male graduates (Education). The median earnings for females in this industry were £32,800 and for males were £36,100. The biggest difference in proportions was in Education, where the proportion of female graduates was 11.9 % points higher than the proportion of male graduates.

The biggest difference in median earnings was in Mining and quarrying, where the median earnings of female graduates were £20,600 higher than the median earnings of male graduates. The group with the highest earnings was Female graduates who worked in the Mining and quarrying industry (median earnings of £88,100). 64.9% of female graduates worked in the top 2 industries (either Education or Human health and social work activities); the equivalent figure for male graduates was 41.6%.
